Computer Graphics 2024/25 — Lab 1

Miles Hansard, QMUL.

This lab is an introduction to WebGL programming, based on simple 2D shapes and animations. The objectives are to become familiar with WebGL project structure, drawing operations, and shader syntax.

Tasks

  • Zip your code folder, to create lab-1.zip, containing your final versions of all code files, plus your PNG images, in the appropriate directories:
A/A1.png ... A/A6.png
B/ ...
etc
  • Write a short lab report to summarize your work, and upload it in PDF format. Include each of your output images in the corresponding section A1, A2, …, etc, with the summary underneath or alongside. There is a 250 word limit for each summary (they can be shorter). You may include snippets of code, as well as diagrams and equations, where appropriate. There is a Model answer for task A0 (which you do not need to include in your report).
  • The questions that appear in the tasks are prompts for issues to discuss in the report, in addition to your own observations.
  • Note that your images might not exactly match the examples. For example, the rotation angle may be different, or you might see minor rendering artefacts (due to driver issues). In particular, you might find that the line width cannot be set properly (for reasons explained below). These minor differences do not matter in the marking scheme!

Marking scheme

The lab objectives are listed below. Note that you must achieve all example images, in order to score more than 60. Higher marks are determined by the quality of the report, including content and presentation.

  • 0–60: Some example images achieved, with basic descriptions in the report.
  • 60–70: All examples achieved, with basic descriptions in the report.
  • 70–100: All example images achieved, accompanied by clear and insightful expositions. Correctly formatted report, including links and references where appropriate.

Setup

Unzip (extract) the file lab-1.zip. The folder lab-1/ contains the following files for exercise A:

  • A/rotating-square.html — markup that runs the code, and shows the result in the browser.
  • A/rotating-square.js — JavaScript code that defines the scene, and runs the shaders.
  • A/rotating-shape-vert.glsl — GLSL vertex shader.
  • A/rotating-shape-frag.glsl — GLSL fragment shader.

Open the four files from directory A/, above, in VS Code, or your preferred editor. Similar files are provided for exercises B and C. I strongly advise you to use a pen and paper during the labs. It is much easier to debug vertex indexing etc if you draw a sketch of what is supposed to go where…

Running a local server

Open a terminal in the lab-1 directory (you can do this with ctrl' in Windows VS Code, or ctrl` in Linux VS code). You may need to use the cd command to change directory to lab-1. To start a local server, run the following command in the terminal (assuming that Python is installed):

  • Linux: python3 -m http.server
  • Windows: python -m http.server
  • College PCs: reboot to Linux (recommended), or in Windows: L:\Anaconda\3.9\python.exe -m http.server
  • Now open this URL, in Firefox: http://localhost:8000/. You should be able to find the HTML files, in directories A/ B/, and C/.

Browser settings

Because we will use a local server, it is essential to disable the browser cache (while the dev console is open), so that your shaders can be updated. You only have to do this once; it will be remembered by the browser.

  • Open the console: ctrl-shift-k
  • Open the console settings: F1
  • Tick Disable HTTP Cache (when toolbox is open) in the right-hand column.
  • Click back to Console on the developer bar, at the top.
  • Try changing the fragment shader colour to yellow: gl_FragColor(1.0, 1.0, 0.0, 1.0), to check that everything is working.
  • Reload the page: ctrl-r or F5.
  • Change the colour back to red: gl_FragColor(1.0, 1.0, 0.0, 1.0);
  • Remember to KEEP THE CONSOLE OPEN (ctrl-shift-k) at all times, for debugging.

Exercise A

A0 — User interaction

  • Open the file rotating-square.html in VS Code and Firefox.
  • Open the file rotating-square.js in VS Code.

The set_speed function near the top of the JavaScript file is a callback for the HTML speed selection menu. The three possible values in the HTML selection object are 'slow', 'medium', and 'fast'. The global variable theta_step determines the angular adjustment of the shape, on each frame.

  • Check the console message (ctrl-shift-k) when you change the drop-down selection.
  • Complete the body of the switch statement, in the set_speed function, so that the existing global variable theta_step is set to the value 0.005, 0.01, or 0.02, according to the speed value, respectively.
  • Add a Pause option in the HTML selector, and handle this case in the switch statement, using a suitable number for the angle change. This will be useful when you want save the canvas (or if you find the rotation annoying). You can make this the default, by changing the global initialization of theta_step.

Model answer

A1 — Modifying the drawing procedure

  • Find the line gl.drawArrays(gl.TRIANGLE_STRIP, 0, num_strip_vertices) in the JS render function, and change num_strip_vertices to 3. What is the effect of this change, and what does it show about the construction of the square?

  • Undo the above change, so that you see the square again.

A2 — Modifying the fragment shader

Recall that RGBA colours can be represented by vec4 types, where the fourth value is the opacity (1.0 means opaque). The fragment shader rotating-shape-frag.glsl colours every fragment red:

    gl_FragColor = vec4(1.0, 0.0, 0.0, 1.0);
  • Change the right-hand side to the RGB vector representation of blue, save the file, and reload rotating-square.html.
  • Define RGB (not RGBA) vec3 colours for red and green.
  • Add together (using the + operator) the RGB vectors for red and green, and turn the result into an opaque RGBA vector vec4(red + green, 1.0).
  • Assign the new RGBA vector to gl_FragColor, and refresh the display. What do you see?
  • Restore the original red colour of the square.

A3 — Modifying the vertex shader

  • Add the following two lines, in the vertex shader rotating-shape-vert.glsl after the rotation transformation:
    gl_Position.x *= (1.0 + s) / 2.0;
    gl_Position.y *= (1.0 + s) / 2.0;
  • What effect do you see in the animation? Note that s represents sin(theta), which is a number in the range -1...1. What kind of transformation is performed, by the above lines, on the (x,y) position coordinates?

  • Remove the two lines, added above, from the vertex shader.

A4 — Interpolating colours

  • Add the following lines, at the top of the vertex shader rotating-shape-vert.glsl:
    attribute vec4 colour;
    varying lowp vec4 colour_var;

The first line declares an attribute which will be passed in from the JavaScript code. The second line declares a varying, which will subsequently be interpolated by the fragment shader.

  • Add the following line, inside the main function of the vertex shader:
    colour_var = colour;

This means that the current vertex will contribute this colour to the varying interpolation. The surface colour between the vertices can then be interpolated by the fragment shader, rotating-shape-frag.glsl.

  • To activate the interpolation, declare the incoming vertex colour as a varying, at the top of the fragment shader:
    varying lowp vec4 colour_var;
  • In order to use this variable, change the colour setting in the fragment shader to:
    gl_FragColor = colour_var;
  • Finally, we need to connect the attribute colour data. This has already been prepared in the init JavaScript function. In order to enable the attributes, add the following lines to the render function, just before the triangles are drawn:
    // connect vertex_colour attribute in shader to colour_buf
    gl.vertexAttribPointer(colour_loc, 4, gl.FLOAT, false, 0, 0);
    gl.enableVertexAttribArray(colour_loc);

Make sure that you understand these lines, referring to the documentation for vertexAttribPointer and drawArrays.

  • You should see something like the following image. Note how the colour has been interpolated across the pixels, based on the four vertex attribute colours.

A5 — Vertex indexing

Note that you might see some small notches in your lines, during these exercises, and you might find that your lines are very thin (which means that the gl.lineWidth setting was ignored). Don’t worry: these are driver issues, which won’t affect your marks. Explanation: there is no universal way to daw high quality lines in 2D and 3D, so OpenGL leaves the proper implementation up to the programmer, but we won’t worry about it here.

  • Find the triangle-drawing commands in the JavaScript rendering function:
    let num_strip_vertices = vertices.length; 
    gl.drawArrays(gl.TRIANGLE_STRIP, 0, num_strip_vertices);
  • Comment-out the above lines, and add the following commands, underneath, to draw a 2D line, along the first (red-green) edge of the square.
    gl.vertexAttribPointer(colour_loc, 4, gl.FLOAT, false, 0, 0);
    gl.enableVertexAttribArray(colour_loc);
    let num_line_vertices = indices.length;
    gl.drawElements(gl.LINES, num_line_vertices, gl.UNSIGNED_SHORT, 0);

Note the change from direct drawing with gl.drawArrays to indexed drawing with gl.drawElements. Refer to the documentation for drawElements. The indices array in the init JavaScript function looks like this:

    var indices = [
         0, 1
         ];

which means that a single line, will be drawn, between vertices 0 and 1.

  • Fill-in the the rest of the indices, to draw the other six lines, as shown below:

A6 — Drawing an outline

We can use the same shaders to colour the lines, by adding new RGBA values to the end colours array, and telling the shader to start from the appropriate offset (instead of starting from the beginning of the array).

  • Add six RGBA opaque black quadruples to the end of the colours array, in the init function.
  • The correct offset to use, in the vertex colour buffer, is the number of bytes to skip in order to reach the new black entries, as can be seen from the documentation vertexAttribPointer. In this case, the offset should be 4*4*4 = 64, corresponding to:
(number of vertices) * (length of RGBA vec) * (number bytes in Float32)

The second and third terms are constant, so this can be expressed in code as:

    let black_offset = vertices.length * 4 * 4;
  • Add this black_offset definition to the render function, and change the last argument of gl.vertexAttribPointer to black_offset. You should see the same six lines, but all in black.
  • Now uncomment the triangle drawing lines, that were commented-out in A5. You should see the following image:

  • Think about how we created this image. We used two passes of the same shader, but manipulated the vertex attribute data in each case.
  • The varying colour has been interpolated from the vertex attributes of the two triangles. In fact the line-colours are also interpolated, but they appear constant; why is this?

Exercise B

Open the file B/colour-hexagon.js for editing. The same shaders from exercise A will be used (assuming that exercises A1–A6 have been completed). Copy your shaders into the B/ directory.

B1 — Drawing a hexagon

  • The vertices of a hexagon are six equally spaced points on the unit circle. Turn the following pseudocode into JS, using a for loop, and use it to generate the vertices[] array in colour-hexagon.js:
    num_vertices = 6
    k = 0...num_vertices
    // define an angle that is 0 when k=0 and 2*PI when k=num_vertices
    t = k/num_vertices * 2.0*Math.PI
    // define a point on the circle, at angle t
    P = [ Math.cos(t), Math.sin(t) ]
  • Also define the indices[] array, to work in conjunction with vertices[], bearing in mind that the rendering mode is gl.LINE_STRIP. You should see the outline of a hexagon, like this:

B2 — Colouring the hexagon

  • Next, render a solid hexagon, composed of six triangles. Change the rendering line
    gl.drawElements(gl.LINE_STRIP, num_line_vertices, gl.UNSIGNED_SHORT, 0);

to use the TRIANGLE_FAN drawing mode, and modify the vertices[] and indices[] arrays appropriately (hint: you will need to add an extra vertex).

  • Modify the colours array, so that the vertices of the hexagon are coloured in the following order, going anticlockwise from the right-most vertex:
red, yellow, green, cyan, blue, magenta
  • The shaders from exercise A are used to interpolate the vertex colours across the hexagon. You should see something like this:

Exercise C

C1 — Drawing an octagon

  • The file colour-spiral contains empty vertices and colours arrays. Note that these are configured for direct (not indexed) drawing, with gl.drawArrays.
  • Recall the hexagon code that you wrote in exercise B1. Copy and modify this in the current JS file, to draw an octagon. Make use of the pre-defined global variable num_vertices, which should be set to 8, for the octagon.
  • You should fill the colours array, as well as the vertices. For example, you can use colours.push() to append an opaque red RGBA array [1,0,0,1], for each vertex that is created in the loop.
  • Scale the vertex coordinates by 0.99, so that the result fits nicely in the window (hint P=[0.99*Math.cos(t),0.99*Math.sin(t)]).

C2 — Drawing a circle

  • Modify your vertex loop to draw a circle, by increasing num_vertices to 1000.
  • Note that there is no performance cost, even though the rendering task has increased substantially.

C3 — Drawing a spiral

  • Modify your vertex loop to draw a spiral, with 16 cycles.
  • You need a scale parameter s that goes from 0 to 1, as k goes from 0 to num_vertices. You can use this to scale the [x,y] coordinates, so that the radius of the path increases from 0 to 1 during the loop (you can multiply by 0.99 if you want to stop the end of the spiral from going outside the canvas).
  • The previous angle parameter t needs to go faster, so that it has covered the angle 16*2π by the end of the loop.

C4 — Colouring the spiral

  • Look for the function rgba_wheel(t) in the shared/graphics.js JS file. It generates a continuous colour wheel (list of RGBA vectors), from a parameter t in the range [0,2π]. It is not necessary to understand the details of the function.
  • Use that function to colour the spiral, by calling it with a suitable parameter.

C5 — Drawing a squiral

  • A ‘squircle’ is a shape between a square and a circle. It is a special case of a superellipse. Find the parametric equations, which are functions of the angular parameter t, in the Wikipedia page.
  • Write a squircle(t,n) function, to implement the following pseudocode (note that the power ab is denoted a^b), based on the parametric equations. Your function should return a vector [x,y] of coordinates on the superellipse.
   x(t) = abs(cos(t))^(2/n) * sign(cos(t))
   y(t) = abs(sin(t))^(2/n) * sign(sin(t))
  • If you keep the previous scale factor s, you can draw a square sprial, or ‘squiral’:

  • Try some other settings of the shape parameter n, for example: 0.75, 1, 10, 100.

Exercise D

This is an optional exercise, with no marks, but it will be useful for developing your understanding of the attribute buffer syntax.

D1 — Using interleaved attributes

  • Copy the contents of your C/ directory to a new directory D/.
  • The separate vertices[] and colours[] arrays can always be replaced by a single attribute array. This is more efficient, and arguably more convenient. Replace the separate array initializations with:
    let vertices_colours = [];
  • Push each [x,y] vertex onto the vertices_colours array, directly followed by the corresponding [r,g,b,a] colour, in the for-loop.
  • Re-write the attribute setup functions, using the single vertices_colours array. Here are some hints:
  • The functions gl.createBuffer(),   gl.bindBuffer(), and gl.bufferData() will only need to be called once each.
  • The functions gl.getAttribLocation(),   gl.vertexAttribPointer(), and gl.enableVertexAttribArray() will still need to be called twice each.
  • You will need to work out the correct arguments to gl.vertexAttribPointer(), using the slides. Note that there are 4 bytes in a 32bit float.
  • The resulting image should be the same as before.
